      <hedline>
        <hl1>MACHU PICCHU STILL A MARVEL</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Nancy Neaher Maas letter on Ethan Todras-Whitehill's June 3 travel article on Machu Picchu, Peru</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: I feel that ''The Other Machu Picchu'' (June 3), in which Ethan Todras-Whitehill dismisses the ruins there as overrun by tourists, doesn't tell the full story.</p>
        <p>True, there are more visitors now than in the 1960's when I slept in a sleeping bag among the ruins. However, important sections had not yet been investigated and/or rescued from the wilderness.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: I feel that ''The Other Machu Picchu'' (June 3), in which Ethan Todras-Whitehill dismisses the ruins there as overrun by tourists, doesn't tell the full story.</p>
        <p>True, there are more visitors now than in the 1960's when I slept in a sleeping bag among the ruins. However, important sections had not yet been investigated and/or rescued from the wilderness.</p>
        <p>After subsequent decades of archeological restoration, innumerable ''new'' elements have reappeared. One is the so-called Temple of the Condor, wherein natural rock is manipulated to suggest the great bird with wings outstretched. For me, there is no doubt that Incan ingenuity and artistry are now on display in ways that were not possible 40 years ago.</p>
        <p>Yes, this will be a shared experience with many others, but by picking off-peak hours and hiking nearby trails, the full magnificence of Machu Picchu can still be easily absorbed.</p>
        <p>Nancy Neaher Maas  Ithaca, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
